Modern editions vary in using capital or lower-case letters
for this inscription over the gate of hell.  Lacking Dante's autograph
MS, we can only conjecture.  For the view that the model for these
words is found in the victorious inscriptions found on Roman triumphal
arches, sculpted in capital letters in stone, see Hollander (^Allegory
in Dante&#8219;s "Commedia"~ [Princeton, Princeton University Press,
1969]), p. 300.  In this view every condemned sinner is being led back
captive to 'that Rome of which Christ is Roman' (^Purg~. XXXII.102),
'under the yoke' into God's holy kingdom, where he or she will be
eternally a prisoner.
