The comparison (^come persona accorta~) lends Virgil
authority in two regards: he is aware of Dante's moral shortcomings and
he understands the underworld, since he has descended once before (see
^Inf~. IX.22-27; ^Inf~. XXI.63).  The scene indeed has a classical
precursor, as was noted, among the early commentators, by Boccaccio
(comm. to ^Inf~. III.13-15): the Sibyl's reassurance of threatened
Aeneas (^Aen~. VI.261): 'Nunc animis opus, Aenea, nunc pectore firmo.'
Mazzoni (^Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina Commedia": "Inferno"
--Canti I-III~ [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), p. 342, follows the
tradition in the commentaries which argues that this tercet reaffirms
the moral reading of ^Inf~. III.12, 'Maestro, il senso lor m'&#928;
duro.'
