This first instance of Dante's weeping is part of a program of
the protagonist's development in hell, in which he (very) gradually
overcomes the twin temptations to weep for or feel fear at the
situation of the sinners in Inferno.  See Hollander (^Allegory in
Dante&#8219;s "Commedia"~), pp. 301-7.  In the harsh moral code of the
text, sympathy for the damned is always misplaced, if a certain
admiration for some of their better qualities is allowed.
