The second descriptive passage that indicates the condition
of these sinners continues the ^contrapasso~ (see ^Inf~. XXVIII.142).
Now we see that these beings, who lacked all inner stimulation, are
stung (^stimolati~) by noxious insects.  Their tears mix with the blood
drawn by these wounds only to serve as food for worms.  Dante's
personal hatred for those who, unlike him, never made their true
feelings or opinions known irradiates this canto.  There is not a
single detail that falls short of the condition of eternal insult.
