Dante asks two things of his guide, the identity of those
gathered at the river's bank and the reason for their apparent
eagerness to cross over.  His questions seem more or less similar to
those he had asked at ^Inf~. III.33, when he wanted to know the
identity of the wailing souls who turn out to be the neutrals.  On that
occasion, Virgil answers him immediately; on this, as we soon see, he
is much less forthcoming.  See the note, below, to ^Inf~. III.76-78).
