..REFS:
EN-A10-O3-L112 A10-O3-L112
EN-A10-O3-L113 A10-O3-L113
EN-A10-O3-L114 A10-O3-L114
EN-A10-O3-L115 A10-O3-L115
EN-A10-O3-L116 A10-O3-L116
EN-A10-O3-L117 A10-O3-L117
EN-A10-O3-L118 A10-O3-L118
EN-A10-O3-L119 A10-O3-L119
EN-A10-O3-L120 A10-O3-L120
..TEXT:
Where each of the first two cantos has had two major
similes (^Inf~. I.22-27;  ^Inf~. I.55-60;  ^Inf~. II.37-42;  ^Inf~.
II.127-132), the third canto reserves its similetic energy for this
double simile that describes the final action of the canto, the
departure of the sinners in Charon's skiff.  It is a commonplace that
the third canto is the most 'Virgilian' canto of the ^Commedia~.  In
fact, study has shown that it has more than twice as many Virgilian
citations than any other canto in the poem (see Hollander, "Le opere di
Virgilio nella ^Commedia~ di Dante," in ^Dante e la "bella scola" della
poesia: Autorit&#914; e sfida poetica~, ed. A. A. Iannucci [Ravenna:
Longo, 1993],  pp. 250-51).  This double simile has long been
recognized as involving an amalgam of two Virgilian passages, ^Aeneid~
VI.309-312 and ^Georgics~ II.82.  It has also been understood as being
the 'controling simile' for the entire poem, combining pagan and
Christian elements: see the article by Margherita Frankel ("Biblical
Figurations in Dante's Reading of the ^Aeneid~," ^Dante Studies~ 100
[1982], pp. 13-23).
